         <div type="translation"
              ana="#b1"
              xml:id="zoor0037.translation"
              corresp="#zoor0037.transcription">
            <p>[... having a good name] (and) good faith (at the age) of 20 years, in (the) year
                    272, on (the) 13th (day) of (the) month Peritios, on (the) 3rd day of (the) Lord
                    (Tuesday). Be of good cheer, no one (is) immortal.</p>
         </div>
      </body>
      <back>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>The inscription provides the date as the Third Day of the Lord, on the 13th of Peritios in the year 272 according to the Era of the Province of Arabia, that is, Tuesday, January 28, 378 CE. The tombstone is one of about 700 discovered in Byzantine Zoora. The majority of the Greek tombstones from this location have been identified as Christian. It is in poor condition, and as a result approximately five lines seem to be missing from the top of the inscription. The text, which contains numerous spelling errors, was engraved in a square script. The last three lines of the inscription are squeezed together due to lack of space. In addition to being engraved, lines seven, ten and twelve are also painted red. An engraved and red painted frame encloses the inscription on its sides and bottom. A bird painted in red is found below the bottom right corner of the frame. The year, month day and weekday numerals are all indicated with horizontal bars over the letters. The word ἔτους is abbreviated by the first two letters of the word and the sign S, while Kυρίου is represented with the letters of the word with the first and last with a horizontal bar above them. The author offers a tentative restoration of what he believes to be lines four and five based upon a common epitaph formula. In aside from the reconstruction provided, the first few lines likely included the name and patronymic of the deceased.</p>
         </div>
